 and voice.Through manifestos, experimental texts, and ribald public performance, the vanguardists' work intertwined art, culture, and the politics of the day to produce a powerful brand of aesthetic activism, one that sparked an entire rethinking of the meaning of art and culture throughout Latin America.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics)xLatin America. 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics)zLatin America. 0aLatin American literaturexHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aLatin American literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature, ExperimentalxHistory and criticismxLatin America. 0aLiterature, ExperimentalzLatin AmericaxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterary Criticism. 4aSemiotics & Theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aUnruh, Vicky, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052008794140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091524440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520915244423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520915244/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles